diff --git BLUEPRINT.md BLUEPRINT.md
index 9a4c0be49e..1d8dcf53db 100644
--- BLUEPRINT.md
+++ BLUEPRINT.md
@@ -421,7 +421,7 @@ ## 14. Django Project Workflows
 - **Migration retry with selective faking** for known-stuck migrations, declared per overlay
 - **Post-DB steps** run after import (password reset, fixtures, …) — declared per overlay
 - **State reconciler** (`t3 workspace doctor`) reconciles DB ↔ disk ↔ docker drift on demand
-- **Shared Redis, one DB slot per ticket** — overlays that `uses_redis()` share a single `teatree-redis` container; each ticket claims one Redis DB index from a pool sized by `redis_db_count` (default 64). `ensure_running` recreates a live container started with a smaller `--databases` so a raised pool actually takes effect. Slots are released on teardown, lazily reclaimed before exhaustion, proactively swept by `workspace clean-all` (orphaned slots whose worktree dirs are gone but rows persist), and freed per-ticket via `t3 <overlay> worktree release-slot <ticket>`. `worktree start` heals a `provisioned` worktree whose DB was never created (interrupted provision), and `ServiceLauncher` is single-flight per `(worktree, service)` so concurrent frontend rebuilds never race the output dir
+- **Shared Redis, one DB slot per ticket** — overlays that `uses_redis()` share a single `teatree-redis` container; each ticket claims one Redis DB index from a pool sized by `redis_db_count` (default 64). `ensure_running` recreates a live container started with a smaller `--databases` so a raised pool actually takes effect — but that recreate is **destructive** (stop + rm + create) and would drop the cache + Celery broker state of **every** worktree sharing the container. Because `worktree provision` calls `ensure_running` for every new ticket, the per-ticket path passes `allow_resize_recreate=False` whenever any worktree is live (`services_up`/`ready`, via `Worktree.objects.has_live_stacks()`): a raised pool then degrades gracefully — the new stack uses the slots the container already has and a log line points at the explicit upgrade — rather than silently nuking a concurrent worktree's shared state (#2577). The destructive resize is applied deliberately by `t3 infra redis upgrade`, which refuses while a live stack exists. The publish heal (#1373, a missing `-p 6379:6379`) is *not* a resize — an unpublished container is already broken for everyone — so it recreates regardless of the guard. Slots are released on teardown, lazily reclaimed before exhaustion, proactively swept by `workspace clean-all` (orphaned slots whose worktree dirs are gone but rows persist), and freed per-ticket via `t3 <overlay> worktree release-slot <ticket>`. `worktree start` heals a `provisioned` worktree whose DB was never created (interrupted provision), and `ServiceLauncher` is single-flight per `(worktree, service)` so concurrent frontend rebuilds never race the output dir
 
 ---
 
